The band gaps of N-WCDs aqueous and powder are 4.31 eV and 3.93 eV (Figure S3 a, b), respectively, calculated by Tauc plots fitted by the equation: (αhv)2=A(hv-E

                           0
                        ) [60]. It suggests that the powder aggregates of N-WCDs achieve the transfer of excited state electrons through reabsorption and RET, which creates intermediate band gaps (Fig. 7b), induces long-wavelength emission and attenuates short-wavelength emission. Together with the pristine “core-shell” structure that ensures the self-quenching-resistant feature, the solid-state white light is achieved. The multiple “core-shell” structure of B, N co-doped CDs is capable of generating different intermediate band gaps for the core, edge and surface states, respectively. The band gaps of B, N-WCDs and B, N-RCDs (Figure S3 c, d) are calculated to be 2.70 ev and 2.54 ev. Therefore, we propose a possible model to explain the fluorescence redshift phenomenon, as shown in Fig. 7. From the above structural characterization, it can be concluded that all CDs have similar particle sizes and degree of graphitization. With the fluorescence redshift, –OH, amino N, N–B and C–B gradually increase, while pyrrolic N gradually decreases. It is speculative that the sp2 graphitized carbon structure and pyrrolic N can induce local aberration, resulting in an intermediate band gap corresponding to blue light emission, which corresponds to the core state. More subfluorophores such as amino N, N–B, and C–B generate a few energy levels between the n-π* gaps [55], inducing broad emission peaks from 550 to 650 nm (Fig. 5f), which corresponds to the edge state. The hydroxyl shell formed by massive –OH wrapped on the surface of CDs further achieves red light emission, which corresponds to the surface state. It is noteworthy that B, N co-doping and alkali passivation can induce the conversion of pyrrolic N to graphitic N in CDs, and the graphitic N as an electron-donating element can physically provide additional electrons after replacing the C atoms into the conjugated system, further reducing the band gap and achieving a wider range of fluorescence redshift [43], which corresponds to the emission peak of B, N-RCDs at 712 nm. It can also be verified from XPS and the fluorescence comparison of CDs (Figure S4).
